docs.abstract: A.I. developers are committing to end the injustices in how their technology is often made and used.
docs.snippet: A.I. developers are committing to end the injustices in how their technology is often made and used.
docs.lead_paragraph: On a summer night in Dallas in 2016, a bomb-handling robot made technological history. Police officers had attached roughly a pound of C-4 explosive to it, steered the device up to a wall near an active shooter and detonated the charge. In the explosion, the assailant, Micah Xavier Johnson, became the first person in the United States to be killed by a police robot.

headline.main: Can We Make Our Robots Less Biased Than We Are?
headline.print_headline: Calling for Robots  To Be Free of Bias

docs.abstract: After a wave of anti-Asian discrimination, the artist Amanda Phingbodhipakkiya wanted to “turn these hurts into something beautiful.” Her panels will transform a Brooklyn subway station.
docs.snippet: After a wave of anti-Asian discrimination, the artist Amanda Phingbodhipakkiya wanted to “turn these hurts into something beautiful.” Her panels will transform a Brooklyn subway station.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Tuesday, New Yorkers commuting through the Atlantic Avenue-Barclays Center subway station will find it transformed with vibrant portraits of Black, Asian and Pacific Islander people along with anti-discriminatory messages like “I did not make you sick” and “I am not your scapegoat.”

headline.main: ‘I Still Believe in Our City’: A Public Art Series Takes On Racism

docs.abstract: Ten years ago, the Olori Sisterhood was a small-time “political sorority.” Now they’re ready for a seat at the table.
docs.snippet: Ten years ago, the Olori Sisterhood was a small-time “political sorority.” Now they’re ready for a seat at the table.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last November, when Democratic presidential candidates were still jockeying for the nomination, before the coronavirus pandemic killed more than 250,000 Americans and fervent protests against police brutality swept the nation, Senator Kamala Harris of California appeared before a group of mostly Black women in South Carolina to file officially for the state’s critical primary.

headline.main: How a Brooklyn Sisterhood of Black Women Became National Power Brokers
headline.print_headline: Ready for Their Seat at the Table

docs.abstract: Ottobah Cugoano, who became a writer and campaigner after surviving slavery in the West Indies, has been honored by a heritage program that long focused on white men.
docs.snippet: Ottobah Cugoano, who became a writer and campaigner after surviving slavery in the West Indies, has been honored by a heritage program that long focused on white men.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — An 18th-century antislavery campaigner and author, Ottobah Cugoano, has become the earliest Black figure to be honored with one of London’s iconic blue plaques, the heritage organization that manages the program said on Friday.

headline.main: Abolitionist Is Earliest Black Londoner Honored With Blue Plaque
headline.print_headline: In London, Iconic Honor For Pioneer In Abolition
